  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="KT33-kilavi">vāyilākap pukka pāṇaṉ kēṭpat tōḻiyai nōkkit talaimakaḷ vāyil nērvāḷ kūṟiyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">SHE talking as one who grants mediation/the door, looking at the confidante, [but] for the bard to hear who has entered as a mediator.</p>
          </div>



        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="KT33">
<l>                aṉṉā yivaṉō riḷamā ṇākkaṉ</l>
<l>                ṟaṉṉūr maṉṟat teṉṉaṉ kollō</l>
<l>                virantū ṇirampā mēṉiyoṭu</l>
<l>                virunti ṉūrum peruñcem malaṉē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
               <l>Mother, 
                <choice>
                    <seg>this one,</seg>
                    <seg>regard this one</seg>
                </choice>
                but a young student,<note place="foot">Tradition here takes <term xml:lang="ta">ōr</term> as a verbal root in the function of an imperative for ōr "regard". TVG mentions as parallels Nacc. on Cīvak. 204 and Nacc. on Kali 81.</note></l>
               <l>on the meeting place of his village, what [is] he?</l>
               <l rend="indent">With a body not replete from food by begging,</l>
               <l>going for a feast he [is] great, a superior one.<note place="foot">Considerable exegetical capers (exercised silently by the <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷavi</term> and Cām.) are necessary to relate this strange poem to a bard received favourably. The wording points to an erotic and moreover socially taxing fancy for someone begging food (who, as she says, need not be a beggar, but can be in the position of a student – which, however, sounds rather North-Indian). This is also one of the few poems free from formulae, though <term xml:lang="ta">aṉṉāy</term> as a beginning is also recorded in AN and AiN.</note></l>

                
                </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
